nagement Study — Keziah Vickraman, 2025","navbar":{"background":"#17408B","foreground":"#FFFFFF","title":"🏀 Bench the Instinct","left":[{"text":"Home","href":"index.qmd"},{"text":"Did Load Kill the Achilles?","href":"part1_causal.qmd"},{"text":"Bench the Instinct","href":"part2_predictive.qmd"},{"text":"🏀 The Dashboard","href":"app.qmd"}],"right":[{"text":"📄 Submission","href":"submission.qmd"},{"text":"Revision Log","href":"revision_log.qmd"},{"icon":"github","href":"https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO_NAME","aria-label":"GitHub"}],"logo":{}},"page-footer":{"background":"#17408B","foreground":"#FFFFFF","left":"Keziah Vickraman · Capstone 2025","center":"*We know load caused the spike. Now we know who's next.*","right":"Built with [Quarto](https://quarto.org)"}},"format":{"html":{"theme":{"light":["flatly","assets/custom.scss"]},"toc":true,"toc-depth":3,"toc-title":"On this page","toc-location":"right","code-fold":true,"code-tools":true,"code-copy":true,"code-overflow":"wrap","highlight-style":"github","fig-align":"center","fig-cap-location":"bottom","df-print":"paged","smooth-scroll":true,"anchor-sections":true,"number-sections":true}},"theme":{"light":["flatly","assets/custom.scss"]},"toc-title":"On this page","toc-location":"right","code-copy":true,"fig-cap-location":"bottom","smooth-scroll":true,"anchor-sections":true,"title":"Predicting Load-Related Game Unavailability in the NBA","subtitle":"A Causal and Predictive Analysis of Achilles Injury Burden","date":"2025","author":[{"name":"Keziah Vickraman","affiliations":[{"name":"[Your Institution]"}]}],"abstract":"Achilles tendon ruptures represent some of the most severe and career-disrupting\ninjuries in professional basketball. The 2024–25 NBA season recorded eight confirmed\nruptures — nearly six times the historical per-season average of 1.36. This study\ninvestigates the role of player workload in driving this spike using two complementary\nanalytical frameworks. First, a Difference-in-Differences (DiD) design is used to\nestimate whether the shift toward higher rolling-minutes loads and more frequent\nback-to-back scheduling has causally contributed to elevated rupture rates,\nparticularly since 2016 when systematic load management emerged as a league concern.\nSecond, a hurdle model is trained on 23 seasons of NBA box score data (2002–2025)\nto predict individual player game unavailability — operationalised as the percentage\nof team games missed in a season — using the same load features that explain the\npopulation-level trend. The causal analysis finds directionally positive DiD\ninteraction coefficients for high-load × post-2016 player-seasons, with amplification\nin back-to-back contexts. The predictive model achieves meaningful discrimination on\na held-out temporal test set (2020–2025), with prior missed games, rolling minutes,\nand career tenure emerging as the strongest predictors. Together, these analyses\nprovide a data-driven foundation for proactive load management decisions in elite\nbasketball.\n","keywords":["NBA","Achilles tendon","load management","difference-in-differences","hurdle model","sports analytics","injury prediction"],"bibliography":["references.bib"],"csl":"apa.csl"},"extensions":{"book":{"multiFile":true}}}}